[1] Israel, described outbreak in chickens
Date: Wed 22 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Poultrymed.com, 21 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://poultrymed.com/files/index.html>

HPAI (H5N1), 1st Outbreak In A Broiler Flock In Israel
-----------------------------------------------
Between 10 and 15 Mar 2006, the HPAI-H5N1 virus appeared suddenly in
several turkey flocks in different areas in the southern part of Israel.
Despite the fact that quarantine was declared within an area of 3 km from
the affected turkey farms, the disease appeared in a big broiler farm by 19
Mar 2006.
The farm is situated in a southeast direction and about 4 km from the 1st
outbreak in turkeys [Ein Hashlosha]. The broiler farm is a 160 000 broilers
unit with 13 chicken houses of different types from controlled environment
to conventional. The flock was about 40 days of age, and part of it was
already sent to the slaughterhouse.
Due to the appearance of the H5N1 virus at the turkey farm, the marketing
of the broilers was stopped, and PCR tests were performed before
continuation of marketing was permitted.
Despite the fact that the PCR results proved negative in the sample tested,
2 days after the samples were taken, a sudden increase in mortality was
observed in one out of 10 chicken houses. In a house containing 16 000
broilers, mortality increased from 10 birds per day to 400 the next day to
more than 800 by the 2nd day.
The only clinical signs within the flock were the sudden mortality of
apparently well-developed birds, with severe signs of cyanosis and ischemia
in the wattles, the comb, the legs and the skin of the belly (see pictures).
The tarsal and metatarsal areas were swollen and purple in color (see
pictures).
Post mortem examination did not reveal any special macroscopic change, and
only in some birds a slight grayish discoloration of the pancreas could be
seen.
Tracheal and cloacal swabs taken from sick birds proved positive by PCR
test to the H5N1 HPAI virus.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This firsthand description might be helpful to poultry health specialists,
especially in view of the crucial importance of early detection of 1st
cases in previously unaffected countries. For the pictures, go to the above
URL.
The evolvement of the outbreak in Israel, a non-AI-vaccinating country with
a highly intensive, dense poultry industry (annual turnover of almost USD
600 million) and a relatively advanced animal health infrastructure,
deserves a close, instructive follow-up by industrialized countries. The
1st stages seem to be strikingly reminiscent of the UK 2001 FMD panzootic
(including the political ramifications, 2 weeks prior to general
elections!) with, on top of poultry and not mammals being the subject, one
important difference: the potential zoonotic implications of avian influenza.
On Wed 22 Mar 2006 evening, the Israeli TV and other media sources reported
that a 7th outbreak was suspected in moshav Beqaot, the Jordan Valley
(interactive map at
<http://www.eyeonisrael.com/>, click square 7).
Initial PCR tests indicated H5, but in view of the low mortality observed,
tests are being repeated. See
<http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3231051,00.html>.
- Mod.AS]
